Finally, per the UN, people in low-income economies are "at least 4x more likely to be displaced by extreme weather."Not everyone can afford to prepare for the financial effects of a rapidly evolving climate‚Äîbut if you can set aside a bit of cash, you likely won't regret it.

Building an emergency kit adds up fast.A hand crank radio costs around $35 and a basic first-aid kit goes for about $25. Tack on bottled water, medicine, and other necessities, and you might be waving goodbye to your entertainment budget for the month.

Property damage can be costly. The White House found that the US gov could spend as much as an extra $128B each year in natural disaster relief.Also, people living in areas prone to extreme weather events have to shell out more for insurance than people in other regions.

Energy costs are rising. Last year, unprecedented winter weather knocked out huge segments of the Texas power grid.A 2019 study by the IIASA concluded that climate change will increase demand for energy around the world by 2050‚Äîeven if the overall temperature change is modest.

That‚Äôs basically why I think Climate Change Education & Climate Literacy is so important across all age groups üôÇUnderstanding mental models, pre-, alternative, mis-conceptions can help us to address them better with matching learning environments 14/14

Media as a source of information, judgmental heuristics, or fuzzy environmentalism (the tendency to consider all environmentally harmful acts together) can be named as further reasons for peoples‚Äô fragmented knowledge. 13/14

Other reasons for  conceptions are inaccurate information provided in edu. environments, lack of a clear climate curriculum. Various studies report mis-concepts of pre-service teachers, limited syst. thinking skills of teachers or existing pre-scientific concepts in books. 12/14

As reasoning about systems that emerge form complex interactions of elements is challenging, people underestimate delays and misjudge long term system impacts and are likely to draw erroneous conclusion about the impact of their personal actions or climate policies. 11/14

Besides the different content domains, understanding climate change requires systems thinking skills (e.g., feedback loops, delays, stock/ flow dynamics, concept of equilibrium) to consider the processes, interactions and project the behavior of a dynamical system). 10/14
When people struggle with these individual concepts, it is even more challenging to understand their interplay and the dynamics between these concepts. 9/14

Other reasons for the fragmented understandings are the intangible nature of envir. phenomena and the multidisciplinary content knowledge needed, incl. physics (types of radiation, conservation/ transformation of energy), geography (e.g.,Albedo), chemistry (greenhouse gases) 8/14

People use embodied schemata/metaphors (eg. glasshouse-model) to understand and model abstract phenomena (e.g., stock/ flow processes), these schemata also shape our conceptual understanding. If these schemata are too simplistic they can reinforce non-scientific conceptions. 7/14

People often assume that visible phenomena, such as smog, water or air pollution, are responsible for climate change even though the key mechanisms involved in the greenhouse effect are not observable. 6/14
Climate change and the greenhouse effect build on abstract chemical and physical processes not visible to the human eye and are not directly linked to our experience. 5/14

This issue of non-immediacy does not only apply to climate change, but also to other environmental problems. Even changes that are theoretically noticeable (e.g., biodiversity loss, water pollution) often remain unnoticed by most people. 4/14

The time & spatial scale (local to global) are beyond our human everyday concern, both makes CC cognitive challenging to grasp. People confuse weather and climate as they use their day-to-day experiences of specific weather events rather than considering long-term effects. 3/14

Climate is a statistical aggregated average of weather observations in more or less defined geographical areas over long periods of time. Hence, causes and effects of climate change can only be observed with delays and are difficult to attribute. 2/14
